{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_groomcreek_ver04/data/sn96060774/00414218258/1930110701/0127.xml":{"full_text":"POPULATION\nit Am bos\nNOGALES\nIS 24,701\nGREAT FASHION SHOW IN NOGALES TONIGHT\nMERCHANTS DISPLAY TONIGHT\nTO BE GALA CARNIVAL EVENT\nEntire City Will Turn Out To Witness\nMagnificent Exhibits Prepared\nIn Stores And Shops\nJr. a stupendous effort to revive\nbusiness and prove to the public\nthe high purchasing power of the\ndollar today as compared with a\nyear ago, the merchants of Nogales\nare cooperating 100 per cent in pro\nviding for this city its first Merch\nants\u2019 Display Night event tonight.\nProm 7 until 9 o\u2019clock the two\nmain thoroughfares of the business\ndistrict \u2014Morley and Grand avenues\n\u2014will take on the appearance of\na huge fashion show. The carnival\nspirit will reign and it is expected\nthe entire city will turn out to wit\nness the magnificent exhibits and\nenjoy the program prepared for\nthem by the progressive business\nmen of Nogales.\nMusic will be furnished at prom\ninent places in the business area by\nthe 25th Infantry band and the\nhigh school band and by three or\nchestras. Many of the stores also\nwill furnish music while the merch\nandise is being shown, as many have\ninstalled radios which will be tuned\nin on stations furnishing lively pro\ngrams. The streets and stores will\nbe brilliantly illuminated and pro\nprietors and their entire clerical\nforces will be on duty for two hours\nto greet the visitors.\nMany of the merchants have gone\nto considerable trouble and expense\nto provide a real treat for the pub\nlic and some pleasant surprises are\nin store.\nLa Tille de Paris\nAt La Ville de Paris store, for in\nstance, there will be a real fashion\nshow, with latest creations from\nParis exhibited on living models.\nThe models, selected from among\nthe most attractive girls in Nogales,\nwill parade up and down a carpeted\nfloor in the store\u2019s large show win\ndow and also on an elevated plat-'\nform in the store itself. This dis\nplay of the very latest in fall .and\nwinter garments would do credit to\nany city many times the size of\nNogales.\n888 Department Store\nHoliday gift goods will be at\ntractively featured at the 888 De\npartment Store. Suitable Christmas\ngifts for every member of the\nfamily will be artistically displayed\nand visitors can easily make up their\nBUILDING ACTIVITY IN NOGALES\nANOTHER SIGN BUSINESS GAIN\nAn important factor in business\nrevival is building construction and\nthe building projects now under way\nin Nogales and those planned indi\ncate that this branch of business\nis holding up exceedingly well. While\nNogales continues its building pro\ngram. construction in the northern\ncities has had to stop because of\nsevere weather conditions, which is\nthe usual thing for this time of the\nyear, and activity in the north can\nnot be resumed before spring. Due\nto the ideal Nogales climate, con\nstruction will go right along all win\nter as usual.\nForemost among the building pro\njects now under \u00bbvay is the $30,000\nElks building cn Arroyo boulevard,\nc pposite the Nogales International,\nconstruction of which is being push\ned rapidly. This handsome structure,\nwhich will be two stories in height\nand of modem construction, will\ntie finished shortly after the first\nof the year. The Elks are raising\nSIO,OOO to furnish the new home in\nkeeping with the style of the build\ning itself.\nWork of constructing the two new\ngaritas at the Grand and Morley\navenue international gates is being\npushed to completion by Contrac\ntor Jose Castelan. These attractive\nbuildings are being erected for the\ngovernment. They will be used by\nthe border inspectors and they re\nplace the smaller and out-of-date\nIRogales If n ter national\nVOL. 6\u2014NO. 48 SIX PAGES\ngift lists from the large and varied\nassortment.\nBrackers Army Store\nMen\u2019s fall and winter clothing of\nthe very latest cuts and fabrics will\nbe foremost in the display at Bra\nckers Army Store, and outing wear,\nwork clothes and hunting supplies\nwill also be featured, with the com\npany\u2019s new low prices emphasized\nthroughout.\nOwl Drug Store\nWhile the windows and the en\ntire store have been re-arranged for\n(Turn To Page Five)\nNephew Killed In\nAuto Accident\nEsteban Padres, 25 years old,\nmember of a very prominent family\nof Mexico City, was instantly killed\nin an automobile accident there last\nSaturday, according to a telegram\nreceived by Miss Carmen Gonzales\nand her brother, Charles Gonzales,\nof the Nogales Grocery Company.\nThey are the sister and brother of\nyoung Padres\u2019 mother.\nNo details of the accident were\nlearned here.\nYoung Padres w\u2019as educated in\nAmerican colleges and W'as just be\nginning on a very promising career\nin the business world. He was con\nnected with the Banco de Londres\nat Mexico City.\nRecent Rains Help\nCrop Conditions\nAlong West Coast\n\u2018\u2022Things have changed for the bet\nter and our slump will soon be his\ntory.'\u201d\nThis report was received by the\nMexico-Arizona Trading company\nthis week from one of its represent\natives on the West Coast of Mexico.\nThis company reports that there\nis plenty of water in that section\nnow and crop conditions are very\nencouraging, as a result of the re\ncent rams. Rice and truck farming\nconditions are particularly good,\nwhereas a few' weeks ago the farm\ners were very much discouraged ov\ner the long drought.\ngaritas which were formerly used.\nThe new O'Keefe apartments on\nWest street have just been com\npleted and they are as modern and\nattractive as most apartments to be\nfound in cities much larger than\nNogales. They are equipped with all\nof the modern conveniences.\nConstruction of the new club\nhouse of the Nogales Golf Coun\ntry Club, five miles north of the\ncity on the Tucson road, will be\nfinished Monday or Tuesday. This\nwill be an exceedingly attractive\nbuilding and will be modern in ev\nery respect.\nPlans for the new school build\ning at Calabasas have been approv\ned and bids will be asked for a\nbout December 1. This building will\ncost about SIB,OOO or more.\nRemodeling of La Barata store on\nMorley avenue, which was damaged\nby fire several months ago is now\nunder way.\nMany other minor construction\njobs are now under way in differ\nent parts of the city.\nWhile it is too early to give out\ndefinite details at this time, Con\nti actors Jose Castelan, John W.\nPhillips and Leo Kines say they are\nfiguring on a number of new pro\njects, construction of which will be\ngin within the next thirty or sixty\ndays.\nDemocrat To Be Next Chief Executive Os Arizona\n0 o%' -J&M v\nS\nGEORGE W. P. HUNT\nHon. George W. P. Hunt, Arizona's Grand Old Man. will begin s rving his seventh term as govern\nor in January, as a result of defeating Gcv. John C. Phillips. Republ can. at Tuesday's election. Hunt\nwon in practically every county an.l carried the entire state Democra ic ticket to victory.\nDEMOCRATIC CYCLONE HITS STATE AND NATION\nALL DEMOCRATS EXCEPT 3 WIN IN THIS COUNTY\nDemocrats Capture Numerous Seats\nIn Congress; George W. P. Hunt\nDefeats Phillips\nfiL Democratic eyeJoiie swept\nthe nation Tuesday.\nThroughout the United States,\nDemocratic governors were elec\nted by the wholesale, the Demo\ncrats made big gains in the\nSenate and the national Bouse\nof Representatives and may have\ncaptured enough seats to con\ntrol the next Congress.\nIn Arizona, George W. P.\nHunt, Democratic candidate for\nGovernor, defeated Gov. John\nC. Phillips, Republican candi\ndate for re-election, by a ma\njority of approximately 2,600.\nWhite Defeats Fraizer\nScott White, democratic candidate\nfor Secretary of State, defeated I. P.\nPraizer, Republican, of Nogales. TL\nentire state Democratic ticket was\nelected, each of the Democrats get\nting a handsome majority.\nIn Santa Cruz County the Dem\nocrats elected the entire ticket ex\ncept the supervisors in Districts\nNos. I and 2 and County Recorder.\nAfter January 3 the Board of Su\npervisors will consist of one demo\ncrat and two Republicans instead\nof an entire Ecard of Republicans\nas at present.\nThe vote received by each candi\ndate in this county appears else\nwhere in today's paper.\nElection Sidelights\nFranklin D. Roosevelt, Democrat,\nwas re-elected Governor of New\nYork by the greatest plurality ever\ngiven a gubernatorial candidate in\nthe Emplie state.\nUnited States Senator Heflin was\nNOGALES, ARIZ., FRIDAY, NOV. 7,1930\ndefeated for re-election in Alabama\nby Bankhead. Democrat. Heflin was\nthe Senator who vigorously opposed\nhe Democratic presidential nominee.\nA1 Smith, two years ago. This year\nhe sought re-election as an Inde\n(Turn To Page Three;\nDefinite Signs Os\nBusiness Revival\nMore definte indications of busi\nness revival in Nogales are found in\nthe monthly business statistics for\nOctober just compiled by the cham\nber of commerce.\nThe report shows bank clearings\nfor the month totalled $4,707,055.09,\nas compared with $4,537,392.87 for\nSeptember.\nBuilding permits for the month\nwere $2,550.00 as against $1,600.00\nfor October last year.\nThe movement of commerce thru\nthis port also showed a marked in\ncrease over that of the previous\nmonth. The figures for October\nwere $1,135,830.00 as compared with\n$1,078,271.00 for September.\nPostal receipts also showed a gain.\nRecepts for last month were $3,139-\n.24 as against $2 206.49 for the pre\nvious month.\nMining activities in Santa Cruz\ncounty also showed signs of revival\nthe past month, according to this\nreport cn conditions.\nCounty Agent J. P. Sexton also\nreports farming conditions much\nimproved at the present time.\nForget-Me-Not Day\nFor War Veterans\nIn City Saturday\nTomorrow is Forget-Me-Not Day\nin Nogales and throughout the day\nfifteen of the city's leading young\nsociety girls will sell forget-me-nots\nin the down town district to help\nraise money for the disabled wai\nveterans.\nIn charge of the campaign in No\ngales is Dr. Anna May Smock of\nthe Woman\u2019s Club and she is being\nassisted by a number of other pro\nminent women and also by the lo\ncal American Legion post.\nDr. Smock has received from the\nstate headquarters of the Disabled\nAmerican Veterans of the World\nWar 2500 forget-me-nots and bad\nges to be worn by the girls who\nwill conduct the sale tomorrow.\nA proclamation calling attention\nto Foregt-Me-Not Day and asking\nthe public to respond generously\nwas issued by Mayor H. J. Karns.\nDr. Smock announced that prizes\nwill be awarded the two girls turn\ning in the largest amount of contri\nbutions. There is no stipulated a\nmount to be paid for the flowers.\nThe public is asked to give as liber\nally as it can.\n1931 Auto License\nTags Ready Soon\nThe supply of 1931 auto license\ntags for owners of cars in Santa\nCruz county will arrive within a few\ndays from the office of the state\nhighway department at Phoenix, ac\ncording to County Assessor Harry\nFarrier.\nEvery caito owner will be expect\ned this year to secure license plates\nbefore January 1.\nFIVE CENTS A COPY\nCITY JOINS NATION IN MOVE\n10 END MISS SLIP\nLow Prices Emphasized To Show\nHigh Purchasing Power i\nOs Dollar Today\nBy AL KIRK\nThe very latest styles in men's,\nHow Races Went\nIn This County\nResults of the general election\nTuesday in Santa Cruz County:\nCONGRESS\nDouglas, D 899\nJUSTICE SUPREME COURT\nLockwood, D. 843\nJenckes, R 246\nJUDGE SUPERIOR COURT\nO\u2019Conner, D 1088\nGOVERNOR\nHunt, D 908\nPhillips, R 913\nSECRETARY OF STATE\nWhite, D 771\nFraizer, R 996\nSTATE TREASURER\nSimms, D 1128\nEly, R 529\nSTATE AUDITOR\nFrohmiller, D. 1241\nATTORNEY GENERAL\nK. Berry Peterson, D 1248\nSUPT. PUBLIC INSTRUCTION\nCase, D 1034\nLambert, R 625\nCORPORATION COMMISSIONER\nHcw\u2019e, D 953\nMcKinley, R 538\nMINE INSPECTOR\nFester, D 1131\nSparkes. R 529\nSTATE SENATOR\nCrenshaw, D 1028\nSmith, R 722\nREPRESENTATIVE\nEohlinger, D. 1213\nStcltz, R 526\nSUPERVISOR\nMiddleton, District No. 1, R 459\nJung, District No. 1, D 318\nHannah, District No. 2, R 327\nHarrison, District No. 2, D 257\nRoath, District No. 3, D 243\nHenderson, Distriict No. 3, R. 197\nSHERIFF\nWager. D 1176\nNoon, R 626\nCOUNTY TREASURER\nDumbauld, D. 1280\nCLERK OF COURT\nLee, D 1322\nCOUNTY ATTORNEY\nThurman, D 1133\nLittle, R 607\nCOUNTY RECORDER\nJones, R 975\nMitchell, D 795\nSCHOOL SUP\u2019T\nLerimore, D 1329\nASSESSOR\nFarrior, D 1329\nJUSTICE PEACE, PCT. NO. 1\nHardy, D. 935\nCONSTABLE, PCT. NO. 1\nLarcom, D 751\nStewart, R 403\nFIRE HAZARDS IN NOGALES LESS\nTHAN ANY CITY OF SIZE IN STATE\nAs far as a possible general con\nflagration is concerned, there are les\nfire hazards in Nogales than in any\ncity of this size in the state of Ari\nzona, in the opinion of F. Rives\nHeath, insurance surveyor of the\nPacific department of the Sanborn\nMap company, who has been here\nfrom San Francisco for the past\nthree months surveying the city and\npreparing a new insurance map of\nNogales.\nMr. Heath went on to explain that\nthere are practically no frams build\nings in the city, not even in the\nresidential sections, as most struc\ntures are built of brick or adobe,\nwhich are very fire resisting.\nThe previous insurance map of\nNogales was made thirteen years\nago and required but 11 pages to\ncomplete the job, while Mr. Heath,\nin making the new map, used 22\npages, showing the city has exactly\ndoubled in size in that length ot\ntime. Comparing the new map with\nthe old, it is also shown that the\ncharacter of buildings, particularly\nin the business district, has improv\nSUMMER RESORT\nNogales is a summer resort (or\nresidents of the West Coast of\nMexico\nwomen\u2019s and children\u2019s apparel, the\nlast word in hats and footwear and\nthe newest novelties suitable for the\nholiday season will be shown in most\nattractive fashion tonight when the\nmerchants of Nogales dress up their\nplaces of business for the first Mer\nchants\u2019 Display event ever held in\nthis city.\nThe event is Nogales\u2019 part in the\nnation-wide movement to stimulate\nbusiness\u2014to bring the public to the\nrealization of the fact that business\nhas turned the corner\u2014that prices\ntoday are actually on rock bottom\nand that now is the time to loosen\nup the purse strings and begin buy\ning the necessities of life.\nIt is not the purpose of this move\nment to try and induce the people\nto permiscuously squander their\nmoney. Advocates of the enterprise\nemphasize the point that this is not\nthe object in view at all. No one is\ntrying to give the impression that\nthis country is on the verge of a\nbeam or a wild buying era. It is far\nfrom that. It is a cool, concerted ac\ntion by the business interests of the\nUnited States to try and show the\npublic that there is no logical rea\nson for a continuation of the busi\nness depression. It is pointed out\nthat there is just as much money\nin the country and just as valuable\nnatural resources as there were be\nfore this business lull began. It is\nthe opinion of the leaders who in\naugurated this movement that the\npresent stagnation of business is\nvery largely psychological and that\nif the state of public mind can be\nmade to realize this fact, the up\nward turn which undoubtedly has\nstarted in many sections, will con\ntinue to gain momentum and with\nin a surprisingly short time business\nwill be running on an even keel\nagain and a state of normalcy will\nhave been firmly established.\nSuch a movement cannot, by the\nvery nature of things, be made a\nj success by a few business men in\neach community. In fact the busi\nness men, the merchants, in Nogales\nas in every other community, can\nonly take the lead. They can suggest\nthe remedy for the business ills, but\nit remains for the public to supply\nthe cure.\nUnder the leadership of the mer\nchants\u2019 division of the Nogales\nchamber of commerce, the move\nment in this city thus far has prov\nen a success even beyond expecta\ntion and the mechants say this is\ndue very largely to the untiring ef\nfortrs of E. S. Edmonson, chairman\nof the special committee having di\nrect charge of the campaign. Mr.\nEdmonson, in turn, shifts the credit\nto his committeemen. Nevertheless,\n(Continued on Page 4)\ned remarkably. All of the old flimsy\nconstructed \u201cfire traps\u2019\u2019 have been\nremoved from the down town dis\ntrict and replaced by handsome new\nmodem buildings of Class A, Class\nB and Class C construction. All of\nthe principal city streets have been\npaved and sidewalks laid and, as\nMr. Heath pointed out, the city now\nhas a very substantial water supply\nand fire hydrant system and a most\nefficient fire department, with up\nto-date fire-fighting equipment and\na splendid force of firemen and vol\nunteer firemen.\nThe map prepared by Mr. Heath\nwill be sent to his head office and\nhundreds of copies will be made\nfrom it and distributed among the\nfire insurance companies all over\nthe county.\nUpon the information furnished\nby this map the fire insurance rate\nof Nogales will be based, according\nto Mr. Heath, who explained that\nthis will just be the \u201ckey rate' 1 for\nthe city. The rate on each building\nwill be governed by the condition of\nthat building.","height":"25437","width":"18093"}}
